<section xml:id="linked-lists_simple-linked-list-remove-start"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Removing the First Node</title>

  <p>Now that we have some data, we need to be able to remove it. In a linked list, the easiest place to work is at the start of the list as that is where we have direct access via the head pointer. So we will focus on removing the first node.</p>

  <p>
    There are two main things that need to happen when we remove the first node from a linked list:
    <ul>
      <li>We need to update the head pointer so that it points to the second node in the list (or to <pf>nullptr</pf> if there is no second node).</li>
      <li>We need to delete the old first node to free up the memory it was using.</li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>
    Notice that updating the head pointer has to worry two cases:
  </p>

  <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
    <figure>
      <caption>Case 1: Removing the first node from a list with multiple nodes.</caption>
      <image source="images/linked-list/simple-linked-list-insert-4.svg">
        <shortdescription>
          <p>Head points to the node containing 6, which points to the node containing 10.</p>
        </shortdescription>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <caption>Case 2: Removing the first node from a list with only one node.</caption>
      <image source="images/linked-list/simple-linked-list-insert-3.svg">
        <shortdescription>
          <p>Head now points to the node containing 10.</p>
        </shortdescription>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </sidebyside>


  <activity>
    <title>Linked List Remove Start</title>
    <p>
      The animation is set to remove the first node from the list. Use <c> > </c> to step through the removal process. Then press <c>Delete Front</c> and continue stepping to delete the second node.
    </p>
    <interactive platform="javascript" 
                design-width="1000"
                 aspect="4:2">
    <script type="module">
      import { LinkedListSimple } from "./external/interactives/data-structures/entry.js";

      let anim = new LinkedListSimple({ initialData: [10, 6]});

      anim.doDeleteFront();
    </script>
    <xi:include href="../../fragments/ds-linked-list-instructions.xml"/>
  </interactive>
  </activity>

  <p>Notice that we need a pointer to keep track of the node that we will be deleting after we update head. If we just do <pf>head = head->next;</pf>, we will lose the address of the old first node and will not be able to delete it:</p>

  <figure>
    <caption>The 6 node is unreachable after updating head.</caption>
    <image source="images/linked-list/simple-linked-list-remove-bad-1.svg"
           width="80%">
      <shortdescription>
        <p>Head points to a node containing 10 as does newNode. The 6 node is now unreachable.</p>
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>If we try to delete the node containing 6 before updating head, we are in even worse shape because we will lose the address of the 10 node:</p>

  <figure>
    <caption>The 10 node is unreachable after deleting the 6 node.</caption>
    <image source="images/linked-list/simple-linked-list-remove-bad-2.svg"
           width="80%">
      <shortdescription>
        <p>Head points to a bad address. The 10 node is now unreachable.</p>
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>So, as the animation shows, we need to:
    <ul>
      <li>Save a pointer to the node we want to delete.</li>
      <li>Update the head pointer to point to the next node.</li>
      <li>Delete the old first node using the saved pointer.</li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>Right before deleting the old first node, the list looks like this:</p>
  
  <figure>
    <caption>toDelete points at the node we will delete. Head points to the next node.</caption>
    <image source="images/linked-list/simple-linked-list-remove-good.svg"
           width="80%">
      <shortdescription>
        <p>toDelete points at the node we will delete. Head points to the next node.</p>
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    As we leave the <pf>removeFirst</pf> function, the <pf>toDelete</pf> variable goes out of scope. As long as we have called <pf>delete toDelete;</pf> before leaving the function, the memory used by the deleted node will also have been cleaned up.
  </p>

</section>